{
  "texts": [
    "A large language model (LLM) is a type of artificial intel- ligence (AI) that uses self-supervised neural networks trained on vast quantities of text to generate human-like responses.",
    "In the future, general-purpose or health care-specific LLMs may increasingly support clinical diagnosis; reduce administration burdens; partially automate electronic communication between patients and clinicians; educate students via didactic instruction or patient simulation; accelerate scientific discovery by helping to formulate, refine, and answer research questions; and enhance health literacy and self-care among patients.",
    "But realizing the potential for LLMs in health care also requires confronting the technology's shortcomings.",
    "These models do not \"think\" for themselves and do not understand the reality they are meant to influence; rather, they predict the next \"token,\" or text unit, in a string.",
    "Because their output carries the grammar, syntax, and aesthetics of believable language, users often accept it as truth."
  ]
}